statement.p:
For the matrix E below, find vectors \vect{b} and \vect{c} so that the system \linearsystem{E}{\vect{b}} is consistent and \linearsystem{E}{\vect{c}} is inconsistent.E=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                -2 & 1 & 1 & 0\\
                3 & -1 & 0 & 2\\
                4 & 1 & 1 & 6
                \end{bmatrix}

We have a variety of theorems about how to create column spaces and row spaces and they frequently involve row-reducing a matrix.  Here is a procedure that some try to use to get a column space.  Begin with an m\times n matrix A and row-reduce to a matrix B with columns \vectorlist{B}{n}.  Then form the column space of A as\csp{A}=
                \spn{\set{\vectorlist{B}{n}}}
                =\csp{B}.  This is not not a legitimate procedure, and therefore is not a theorem.  Construct an example to show that the procedure will not in general create the column space of A.

solution.p:
Choose \vect{x}\in\csp{AB}.  Then by  there is a vector \vect{w} that is a solution to \linearsystem{AB}{\vect{x}}.  Define the vector \vect{y} by \vect{y}=B\vect{w}.  We are set.
                    A\vect{y}
                    &=A\left(B\vect{w}\right)&&
                        \text{Definition of }\vect{y}
                    &=\left(AB\right)\vect{w}&&

                    &=\vect{x}&&
                        \vect{w}\text{ solution to }\linearsystem{AB}{\vect{x}}
                This says that \linearsystem{A}{\vect{x}} is a consistent system, and by , we see that \vect{x}\in\csp{A} and therefore \csp{AB}\subseteq\csp{A}.

Choose \vect{x}\in\csp{A}.  By  the linear system \linearsystem{A}{\vect{x}} is consistent, so let \vect{y} be one such solution.  Because B is nonsingular, and linear system using B as a coefficient matrix will have a solution ().  Let \vect{w} be the unique solution to the linear system \linearsystem{B}{\vect{y}}.  All set, here we go,
                    \left(AB\right)\vect{w}
                    &=A\left(B\vect{w}\right)&&

                    &=A\vect{y}&&
                        \vect{w}\text{ solution to }\linearsystem{B}{\vect{y}}
                    &=\vect{x}&&
                        \vect{y}\text{ solution to }\linearsystem{A}{\vect{x}}
                .  This says that the linear system \linearsystem{AB}{\vect{x}} is consistent, so by , \vect{x}\in\csp{AB}.  So \csp{A}\subseteq\csp{AB}.

statement.p:
Suppose that A is an m\times n matrix and B is an n\times m matrix where AB is a nonsingular matrix.  Prove that

\nsp{B}=\set{\zerovector}

\csp{B}\cap\nsp{A}=\set{\zerovector}
                Discuss the case when m=n in connection with .

solution.p:
First, \zerovector\in\nsp{B} trivially.  Now suppose that \vect{x}\in\nsp{B}.  Then
                    AB\vect{x}
                    &=A(B\vect{x})&&

                    &=A\zerovector&&\vect{x}\in\nsp{B}
                    &=\zerovector&&

                .  Since we have assumed AB is nonsingular,  implies that \vect{x}=\zerovector.

Second, \zerovector\in\csp{B} and \zerovector\in\nsp{A} trivially, and so the zero vector is in the intersection as well ().  Now suppose that \vect{y}\in\csp{B}\cap\nsp{A}.  Because \vect{y}\in\csp{B},  says the system \linearsystem{B}{\vect{y}} is consistent.  Let \vect{x}\in\complex{n} be one solution to this system.  Then
                    AB\vect{x}
                    &=A(B\vect{x})&&

                    &=A\vect{y}&&
                        \vect{x}\text{ solution to }\linearsystem{B}{\vect{y}}
                    &=\zerovector&&
                        \vect{y}\in\nsp{A}
                .  Since we have assumed AB is nonsingular,  implies that \vect{x}=\zerovector.  Then \vect{y}=B\vect{x}=B\zerovector=\zerovector.
